[2] France: spread to Bretagne (Brittany)
Date: Fri 7 Sep 2012
Source: FluTrackers.com "Schmallenberg virus: new Akabane-like virus in cattle, sheep and goats in Europe [summ., edited]
http://www.flutrackers.com/forum/showthread.php?p=467391


Schmallenberg virus [SBV] spreading in France
---------------------------------------------
SBV has spread into Bretagne, a very important dairy region in north-western France.

Farmers saw their dairy cattle develop diarrhea, combined with a drop in milk production.

Test results confirmed SBV.

This event is not overly surprising; experts expected the virus to spread to other regions in Europe, including additional parts of the United Kingdom.

Until recently, Bretagne remained free from SBV.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The FluTrackers.com webpage on SBV, edited and moderated by Gert van der Hoek (who is gratefully acknowledged for drawing our attention to the current development), is an excellent source of information on SBV epidemiology in Europe. The page includes a useful map of the SBV distribution in Europe; its update of 4 Sep 2012 is available at http://www.flutrackers.com/forum/showthread.php?t=183181.

FluTracker.com's information on the spread of SBV to Bretagne is based upon Web-agri (France) at http://tinyurl.com/bn7u9pg.

The spread of SBV in regions which remained free during the previous season, currently reported in Switzerland and parts of France, illuminates 2 issues of significance:
1. Animals exposed to SBV infection last year [2011] are immune; this includes a high percentage of the cattle, sheep, and goat populations in the Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, probably Luxembourg, and certain populations in France and (south western) England.
2. The ruminant populations which escaped last year's infection, are susceptible.

To understand the epidemiology of SBV, a virus which clearly managed to overwinter in north western Europe, research efforts are much in need. This refers in particular to entomology.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of France can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/3m0e. - Mod.AS]
